04625nam a2200649Ia 9781487555634DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875556347 a10.3138/97814875556342doi  a(DE-B1597)690610  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHQ76.2.G4bP74 2024 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a306.76/62094309034qCaOONL223/eng/202309111 aPretsell, Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUrning :bQueer Identity in the German Nineteenth Century /cDouglas Pretsell. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (284 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Terminology -- tURNING -- tIntroduction The Age of the Urning -- tPart One: 1862−1871 -- tChapter One The First Urning: Karl Heinrich Ulrichs, 1825–1895 -- tChapter Two From Page to Personhood: The Transmission of Urningtum, 1864–1868 -- tChapter Three Two Trials: Sensation, Horror, and the Urning in the Public Sphere, 1867–1870 -- tChapter Four Sins of the City: Karl Maria Kertbeny and the Social Cross-Dressers, 1865–1880 -- tPART TWO 1872–1897 -- tChapter Five The Matchmaker of Switzerland: Jakob Rudolf Forster’s Grassroots Activism in Germanic Switzerland, 1878–1897 -- tChapter Six Queering Psychiatry: Autobiographical Lobbying of Richard von Krafft-Ebing, 1864–1901 -- tChapter Seven Belling the Cat: Adolf Glaser’s Discreet Police Liaison in Berlin, 1878–1897 -- tChapter Eight The Comradely Uranian: John Addington Symonds and the English Translation of the Urning, 1889–1893 -- tConclusion The End of the Urning Age -- tTimeline of Events -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1864, the German jurist Karl Heinrich Ulrichs coined the term “urning” as a word for same-sex attracted men. Over the next few years, first anonymously and then publicly, he campaigned against the public persecution of these men. In response, some of his readers took on the urning terminology for themselves and engaged with Ulrichs to negotiate the finer points of their new identities. In Urning, Douglas Pretsell writes of same-sex attracted men in German-speaking Europe who used the neologism “urning” as a personal identity in the late nineteenth century. This was in the period before other terms such as “homosexual” gained currency. Drawing on letters, memoirs, and psychiatric case studies, the book uses first-hand autobiographical accounts to map out the contours of urning society. Urning further explores individual accounts of some urnings who attempted their own forms of activism to transform the world around them , even though they had no formal organization. As the century drew to a close, the efforts of Ulrichs and his urning followers paved the way for the launch of the world’s first homosexual rights organization. Urning argues that the men who called themselves urnings were self-identified, self-constructed agents of their own destinies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGay activistszGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aGay menzGermanyxIdentityxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aEuropean history.  aGerman.  aKarl Heinrich Ulrichs.  aLGBTQ history.  aactivism.  agay history.  agay.  ahistory of Germany.  ahomosexuality.  aidentity.  aqueer history.  aqueer rights.  aqueer studies.  aurning.40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148755563440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487555634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487555634/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles